The paper deals with algorithms for computing maximum flow and minimum cut in graphs, which are fundamental problems in computer science. The use of electrical flows and Laplacian matrices is a common technique in graph algorithms, and suggests that the paper may belong to the cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms) or cs.NA (Numerical Analysis) sub-categories. The focus on undirected graphs and the mention of nearly-linear time algorithms suggests that the paper may also belong to the cs.CG (Computational Geometry) sub-category. The use of approximation algorithms and the mention of previous work by Goldberg and Rao suggests that the paper may belong to the cs.DM (Discrete Mathematics) sub-category. Finally, the mention of the fastest known algorithms for these problems suggests that the paper may also belong to the cs.SI (Social and Information Networks) sub-category, which often deals with optimization problems in graphs.
